WEBVTT

00:02.042 --> 00:03.167
-NARRATOR: Tonight...
-Time to dive, let's go!

00:03.250 --> 00:04.542
...on Beyond Oak Island...

00:04.708 --> 00:06.375
I'm convinced Poverty Island's
worth another go.

00:06.500 --> 00:09.292
This year we were able
to get absolute coordinates.

00:09.375 --> 00:10.417
The lighthouse keeper's son

00:10.542 --> 00:11.750
thought they had
discovered something.

00:11.875 --> 00:13.500
Secret Confederate gold

00:13.583 --> 00:15.417
dumped off Poverty Island.

00:15.542 --> 00:17.292
We've got everything we
need to justify a dive.

00:17.375 --> 00:19.750
-What was it?
.45 billion reasons?
-That's right.

00:19.875 --> 00:21.250
Here we go!

00:22.708 --> 00:23.583
Okay, they found something.

00:26.458 --> 00:29.000
-This very well
could be what we seek.
-Yeah.

00:31.542 --> 00:33.250
All the while
we were growing up,

00:33.375 --> 00:36.583
my brother and I were fascinated
with finding treasure.

00:37.833 --> 00:38.750
RICK:
Pirate treasure,

00:38.875 --> 00:40.417
cursed treasure.

00:40.542 --> 00:42.250
Civil War gold.

00:42.375 --> 00:45.042
-(laughter)
-Since then,
our work on Oak Island

00:45.208 --> 00:47.333
has shown us
there's a world of mysteries...

00:47.458 --> 00:50.250
-Whoa.
-...waiting to be explored.

00:50.375 --> 00:53.250
RICK:
So, we like to reach out
to other treasure hunters.

00:53.375 --> 00:55.500
X marks the spot, right there.
Brilliant.

00:55.667 --> 00:57.583
-MARTY: We want to hear
their stories...
-That's right.

00:57.708 --> 01:00.208
-...and share our insights.
-"Ill-gotten gains."

01:00.375 --> 01:01.792
-RICK: And who knows...
-GARY: I got it.

01:01.917 --> 01:03.667
...maybe we can help them
with their search.

01:03.750 --> 01:05.125
MARTY:
Not only in America.

01:05.250 --> 01:06.958
Wow. That is gold.

01:07.083 --> 01:08.875
-RICK: But all over the world.
-Yeah!

01:09.000 --> 01:10.625
MARTY:
<i>Beyond Oak Island.</i>

01:20.042 --> 01:22.292
MARTY: Matty, Rick,
we have a distinguished

01:22.375 --> 01:25.083
visitor that came
all the way to Oak Island

01:25.208 --> 01:26.542
to talk about something

01:26.708 --> 01:29.792
that I have very much
enjoyed: this is Bob Kreipke.

01:29.875 --> 01:31.333
-Hi, Bob.
-Hey, Bob.

01:31.458 --> 01:33.917
Bob was actually the historian,
the corporate historian

01:34.042 --> 01:35.167
for Ford Motor Company.

01:35.292 --> 01:37.333
So, he's very knowledgeable
about archives

01:37.458 --> 01:39.833
and preserving history
and all these sort of things.

01:39.958 --> 01:41.958
Last summer, Bob and I had a...

01:42.083 --> 01:44.000
I guess it would be corny
to call it

01:44.125 --> 01:46.000
a most excellent adventure,
but, but we had

01:46.125 --> 01:48.167
a great adventure,
we had a lot of fun.

01:48.292 --> 01:49.833
I've come to have
a tremendous respect for him.

01:50.000 --> 01:53.250
He has a passion
for this one treasure,

01:53.375 --> 01:55.958
lost treasure,
and the story around it,

01:56.042 --> 01:58.167
which always
appeals to my brother.

01:58.250 --> 02:00.125
The treasure hunt,
it's in our own backyard,

02:00.208 --> 02:02.125
and I think you know
what I'm talking about.

02:02.208 --> 02:03.500
-Poverty Island.
-Poverty Island.

02:03.625 --> 02:06.417
This is one I was hoping
that you were gonna revisit.

02:06.542 --> 02:09.542
-It's incredible.
-This one is just really fun,

02:09.667 --> 02:10.500
but it would add

02:10.583 --> 02:12.500
a real comment
to the history books

02:12.625 --> 02:13.333
as to what happened,

02:13.500 --> 02:15.000
and, and how the Great Lakes

02:15.083 --> 02:16.750
played a role in what you

02:16.875 --> 02:18.875
wouldn't think they would,
and that would be the Civil War.

02:19.042 --> 02:20.458
Absolutely.

02:22.000 --> 02:27.000
NARRATOR: In 1863, at the height
of the American Civil War,

02:27.083 --> 02:30.167
a Union blockade of
all Southern sea ports

02:30.250 --> 02:32.708
was devastating
the Confederate economy.

02:34.042 --> 02:37.375
However, many historians
believe that France,

02:37.542 --> 02:41.167
which was desperate to obtain
Southern shipments of cotton,

02:41.333 --> 02:44.542
was secretly aiding the rebel
cause by smuggling gold

02:44.667 --> 02:48.458
across the Atlantic Ocean
through Northern channels.

02:48.583 --> 02:52.625
Officially, France was
neutral in the Civil War,

02:52.708 --> 02:54.208
but they were
very dependent upon

02:54.333 --> 02:55.750
Confederate cotton.

02:55.875 --> 02:57.167
They were very interested in

02:57.333 --> 02:58.917
having the Confederacy
actually win the war.

03:00.208 --> 03:03.542
In 1863, Napoleon III
allegedly sent $4.5 million

03:03.667 --> 03:05.750
in gold to help
the Confederates.

03:06.833 --> 03:09.417
But the Union Navy
was very, very effective at

03:09.542 --> 03:13.375
blockading the southern ports,
so they decide they're gonna

03:13.500 --> 03:16.292
get this gold to the Confederacy
through the St. Lawrence,

03:16.417 --> 03:17.833
and they would take it
to the Great Lakes and get it

03:17.917 --> 03:20.917
down to Chicago, and from
Chicago, get it to Richmond

03:21.042 --> 03:23.500
on a train or overland.

03:23.625 --> 03:25.167
NARRATOR: One of these
shipments is believed

03:25.292 --> 03:27.042
to have entered
the Northern region

03:27.167 --> 03:30.333
of Lake Michigan near
a 200-acre landmass known

03:30.458 --> 03:34.583
as Poverty Island when it
was detected by a Union vessel.

03:35.875 --> 03:37.500
A desperate chase ensued.

03:38.917 --> 03:42.667
BOB K.:
Legend has it off of Poverty
Island, the ship carrying

03:42.792 --> 03:46.250
the gold said, "The gun boat's
a lot faster than we are;

03:46.375 --> 03:47.667
"we're gonna be overtaken.

03:47.750 --> 03:50.583
We don't want this falling
in the wrong hands."

03:50.708 --> 03:54.333
So they decided to scuttle it
and throw it overboard.

03:56.125 --> 03:57.708
NARRATOR:
According to researchers,

03:57.875 --> 04:01.333
five wooden chests,
linked together by chains

04:01.500 --> 04:03.958
and containing
as much as $400 million

04:04.042 --> 04:06.000
in today's value,

04:06.125 --> 04:07.958
were lost on
the bottom of the lake,

04:08.042 --> 04:11.792
where they remained undisturbed
for nearly seven decades.

04:13.333 --> 04:17.292
But in 1933, a Milwaukee-based
treasure hunter

04:17.417 --> 04:20.250
named Wilfred Behrens
led a search operation

04:20.375 --> 04:23.042
aboard his ship,
known as the <i>Captain Lawrence,</i>

04:23.167 --> 04:26.333
and reportedly located
the sunken chests

04:26.458 --> 04:28.333
using a diving bell drag line,

04:28.458 --> 04:31.417
just offshore
from Poverty Island.

04:31.542 --> 04:35.333
The operation was witnessed
by an 11-year-old named

04:35.458 --> 04:41.583
Karly Jessen, the son of
the island's lighthouse keeper.

04:41.708 --> 04:43.833
watching the <i>Captain Lawrence,</i>
watching the diving bell,

04:43.958 --> 04:45.167
watching the operations.

04:45.292 --> 04:48.542
One day, something unusual
happened on board.

04:48.667 --> 04:50.833
The crew were out there
hooting and hollering.

04:51.000 --> 04:52.500
The lighthouse keeper's son
thought they had

04:52.625 --> 04:54.208
discovered this lost treasure.

04:54.333 --> 04:57.333
(thunder crashing)

04:57.458 --> 05:02.292
Shortly thereafter,
a storm kicks up and he retreats

05:02.375 --> 05:05.292
back to the lighthouse,
and the next morning they go out

05:05.417 --> 05:07.250
and the <i>Captain Lawrence</i>
is no more.

05:08.833 --> 05:12.292
NARRATOR:
A massive storm battered
the boat, causing it,

05:12.417 --> 05:14.250
along with
its salvaged treasure,

05:14.375 --> 05:16.792
to sink within minutes.

05:16.917 --> 05:19.917
Behrens intended to raise
the vessel, but died

05:20.042 --> 05:22.583
before being able to mount
a successful salvage effort.

05:22.708 --> 05:27.167
To this day, many treasure
hunters are convinced

05:27.292 --> 05:28.750
the gold is still out there,

05:28.875 --> 05:32.167
hidden in the frigid waters
of Lake Michigan.

05:32.292 --> 05:34.625
BOB K.:
No one has found that treasure.

05:34.708 --> 05:36.792
I think if you find
the <i>Captain Lawrence,</i>

05:36.875 --> 05:39.333
we can backtrack and say,

05:39.417 --> 05:41.250
you know what,
the treasure's got to be here.

05:41.375 --> 05:44.583
-This is the spot?
-Right here.

05:44.708 --> 05:45.833
NARRATOR:
One year ago,

05:45.917 --> 05:49.125
Marty Lagina joined
historian Bob Kreipke

05:49.208 --> 05:52.500
to search the southern waters
just off Poverty Island

05:52.667 --> 05:55.542
for evidence of
the <i>Captain Lawrence</i> wreckage

05:55.708 --> 05:58.875
and the lost treasure
using sonar technology.

05:59.000 --> 05:59.750
BOB K.:
Okay, on bottom.

05:59.875 --> 06:02.083
NARRATOR:
Although they detected

06:02.208 --> 06:03.917
a mysterious,
square-shaped object...

06:04.042 --> 06:04.875
BOB K.:
I find that unique.

06:05.000 --> 06:06.417
...compelling evidence of

06:06.542 --> 06:10.833
the ship and the five chests
eluded the search operation.

06:11.000 --> 06:13.833
-Bob, there's a lot of treasure
mysteries in the world.
-Yes.

06:13.958 --> 06:16.958
What was it about
Poverty Island that made you so

06:17.083 --> 06:19.333
passionate about it? You've
been working on this for years.

06:19.417 --> 06:23.792
I think the number of clues
that seemed feasible.

06:25.208 --> 06:28.500
Any orchestrated
treasure hunt is based

06:28.583 --> 06:30.792
on, you know, some smoke.

06:30.875 --> 06:33.083
-You know, there's gotta be...
-(laughs)

06:33.208 --> 06:35.083
This one has credence to it.

06:37.542 --> 06:39.375
NARRATOR:
In addition to being a historian

06:39.500 --> 06:41.000
for Ford Motor Company,

06:41.125 --> 06:43.375
where he worked for 44 years,

06:43.500 --> 06:45.833
Bob Kreipke has been fascinated

06:46.000 --> 06:49.167
with the local lore
surrounding lost Civil War gold

06:49.292 --> 06:51.417
in Lake Michigan
for most of his life.

06:51.542 --> 06:53.833
BOB K.: When I was
about 15 years old,

06:53.958 --> 06:57.500
I read some articles about
this Poverty Island treasure.

06:57.583 --> 07:01.417
And because we vacationed
in this area all the time,

07:01.542 --> 07:04.250
I thought, boy, this
would be pretty interesting.

07:04.375 --> 07:08.500
NARRATOR:
His formal research on
the project began in 1977,

07:08.667 --> 07:10.750
and has included a thorough

07:10.875 --> 07:12.792
examination
of shipping records,

07:12.875 --> 07:15.500
weather reports,
and every related document

07:15.583 --> 07:17.750
in Michigan, Wisconsin,

07:17.875 --> 07:21.167
and the National Archives
in Washington, D.C.

07:21.333 --> 07:24.625
The one thing
about Poverty Island is

07:24.708 --> 07:27.333
I believe it's very doable
to search for this treasure.

07:27.500 --> 07:30.667
You have an island that
doesn't move, and um...

07:30.833 --> 07:32.250
Bob, I hate to interrupt you.

07:32.375 --> 07:34.583
I hate to, but I can't help it.

07:34.708 --> 07:36.500
We have an island
that doesn't move, too...

07:36.625 --> 07:39.167
-(laughter)
-...and it hasn't worked
out yet.

07:39.333 --> 07:42.792
-It hasn't helped.
-But there's a big difference.
-Okay.

07:42.917 --> 07:46.000
The difference with
Poverty Island is, guess what?

07:46.083 --> 07:49.000
We don't have to do drilling.
We don't have to do dynamite.

07:49.083 --> 07:52.333
We don't have to do
seismic scans and that.

07:52.458 --> 07:55.167
And you know what treasure
you're looking for.

07:55.333 --> 07:57.875
-Absolutely.
-We don't have that luxury.
-That's true.

07:58.042 --> 07:59.625
Yeah, we know what it
looks like

07:59.708 --> 08:02.917
and it's not going to be
dangerously deep.

08:03.042 --> 08:05.542
Have you ever seen a figure,
has any historian tried to put

08:05.708 --> 08:07.833
a value to it;
is there a range?

08:07.958 --> 08:11.333
Well, some of the articles
that have been written about it

08:11.417 --> 08:14.792
kind of stick on $400 million.

08:14.917 --> 08:19.708
What I contend is you find
the <i>Captain Lawrence.</i>

08:19.833 --> 08:23.917
We know which way the wind
was coming. We backtrack.

08:24.042 --> 08:25.750
And it had to be close enough
so the guy,

08:25.875 --> 08:27.458
-the kid could see it.
-That's right.

08:27.542 --> 08:28.917
And that's another clue.

08:29.042 --> 08:31.500
It couldn't have been
miles away.

08:31.625 --> 08:34.292
It had to be
right in that strait.

08:34.375 --> 08:36.792
And I believe that
that's where it lies.

08:37.833 --> 08:39.417
So, when you guys
went out before...

08:39.542 --> 08:40.667
Yes, Bob and I
have been talking,

08:40.792 --> 08:42.500
and here's
the difference this year.

08:42.625 --> 08:44.500
-Okay.
-The whole thing goes back

08:44.667 --> 08:46.292
to what the young man overheard.

08:46.375 --> 08:50.500
And so, logically, we thought
he would be near the lighthouse.

08:50.667 --> 08:52.625
The lighthouse
is on the south side of

08:52.750 --> 08:53.625
-the island.
-That is correct.

08:53.708 --> 08:55.458
But it didn't match some

08:55.542 --> 08:58.000
of the other things,
so what we were thinking is

08:58.125 --> 09:01.375
a young kid--
If a ship is near his island

09:01.500 --> 09:02.583
and he's bored to death,
and I'm

09:02.708 --> 09:03.667
sure they were
bored to death.

09:03.750 --> 09:05.208
They were bored to death.

09:05.333 --> 09:06.500
They'd follow it around.

09:06.625 --> 09:07.625
So, there's no reason that

09:07.750 --> 09:09.083
the conversation couldn't

09:09.208 --> 09:12.167
have been overheard here
on the north side of the island.

09:12.250 --> 09:16.750
I believe that the captain
didn't want to dump them

09:16.875 --> 09:19.750
where any Tom,
Dick and Harry would find them.

09:19.875 --> 09:23.833
So he had to be deep enough
that it was not an easy task.

09:23.958 --> 09:25.750
But on the other side
of the coin,

09:25.875 --> 09:28.208
he didn't want to get out
in this deep water up here.

09:29.250 --> 09:30.917
So that's why I
think he scuttled it here.

09:31.042 --> 09:33.500
You know, Bob, the thing
that is quite appealing with

09:33.625 --> 09:35.500
this is it's in the backyard.

09:35.625 --> 09:37.917
Yeah. Well, plus, Rick,
you open those chests,

09:38.042 --> 09:40.667
-you're gonna, you're gonna
learn a lot about history,
-Oh, yes.

09:40.792 --> 09:41.958
about what the heck happened.

09:42.042 --> 09:44.333
-Yes.
-Why did so many people

09:44.417 --> 09:47.167
dedicate so much
time and effort--

09:47.333 --> 09:49.333
and money--
to an enterprise?

09:49.500 --> 09:51.208
Right? There has to be
some truth to it.

09:51.375 --> 09:52.542
Absolutely.

09:52.667 --> 09:54.958
I'm convinced that this is
worth another go.

09:55.042 --> 09:56.708
I know a guy
that I can contribute.

09:56.833 --> 09:58.875
His name is Doug Gossage,

09:59.000 --> 10:00.917
and he's a good
underwater device man.

10:01.042 --> 10:03.292
-He's gonna get us
a magnetometer.
-That'd be great.

10:03.417 --> 10:05.375
MARTY: So, we might be able
to pin it down a little bit.

10:05.542 --> 10:08.125
Now, I think we want
to put eyes in the water.

10:08.208 --> 10:12.375
Get some divers in there
and literally confirm

10:12.500 --> 10:14.750
what we think we see

10:14.875 --> 10:16.958
on our electronic gear.

10:17.042 --> 10:19.000
-Recently certified.
-I'm raising

10:19.167 --> 10:20.833
-my hand.
-BOB K.: Well, there's one pair

10:20.958 --> 10:22.542
-of eyes.
-MARTY: So here's the thing,
big brother.

10:22.708 --> 10:23.917
I want to accompany Bob.

10:24.042 --> 10:26.375
At least, you know,
have a go this time.

10:26.500 --> 10:27.667
-Okay.
-Matty,

10:27.792 --> 10:29.333
-sounds like you're all in.
-(exhales) Yes, sir.

10:29.500 --> 10:30.833
MARTY:
So, unfortunately, I'm gonna

10:31.000 --> 10:32.792
leave you on Oak Island because

10:32.917 --> 10:33.875
-it could take about a week.
-I will hold down the fort.

10:34.000 --> 10:36.167
And I wish you complete success.
I mean,

10:36.292 --> 10:37.500
there's nothing better

10:37.583 --> 10:39.167
than putting a period
at the end of a story.

10:39.333 --> 10:41.208
-Yeah.
-BOB K.: I agree.
-RICK: I would love

10:41.375 --> 10:42.833
that you find that period.

10:42.917 --> 10:45.750
-Okay. Well,
let's go give it a try.
-I love this.

10:45.875 --> 10:49.125
Get me in Lake Michigan.
Let's go.

10:52.917 --> 10:55.333
MARTY: We are
in my old stomping grounds now.

10:55.458 --> 10:56.667
I feel like I'm home.

10:56.750 --> 10:58.083
-This is, like,
your roots, I feel like.
-Yeah.

10:58.208 --> 10:59.542
-This is where I come from.
-You and Rick

10:59.667 --> 11:01.167
grew up in this area,

11:01.250 --> 11:03.958
and so I feel like I'm getting
the full Lagina history

11:04.042 --> 11:06.375
-by being here. Yeah.
-Well, you are,
for whatever that's worth.

11:06.542 --> 11:08.500
NARRATOR:
One week after their meeting

11:08.667 --> 11:10.667
in the war room, Marty Lagina

11:10.750 --> 11:13.167
and Matty Blake
travel to Fairport,

11:13.250 --> 11:16.208
a coastal town
on Michigan's Upper Peninsula.

11:16.375 --> 11:18.250
They'll be joining a team

11:18.375 --> 11:21.083
that's exploring the waters
near Poverty Island

11:21.208 --> 11:22.833
five miles to the south,

11:22.958 --> 11:25.000
searching
for a lost shipment of gold

11:25.125 --> 11:27.292
that was reportedly
thrown overboard

11:27.375 --> 11:30.500
into Lake Michigan in 1863.

11:30.667 --> 11:32.292
Hey, we're almost here.

11:32.375 --> 11:33.875
-There it is.
-MATTY: Oh, I think I see it.

11:34.000 --> 11:35.625
MARTY:
There's the big lake.

11:35.750 --> 11:37.125
I'm back in my old stomping
grounds right here

11:37.208 --> 11:38.625
in the Upper Peninsula
of Michigan,

11:38.708 --> 11:39.750
and we are gonna
have another try

11:39.875 --> 11:41.792
at the Poverty Island treasure.

11:41.875 --> 11:43.917
Last year, we were too wed
to the south side.

11:44.042 --> 11:46.667
We're gonna try the north side
of the island this time.

11:46.750 --> 11:48.833
This, sir, is gonna be fun.

11:49.000 --> 11:50.625
-I can't wait.
-Welcome to Michigan's

11:50.708 --> 11:53.083
-wild and wooly Upper Peninsula.
-(laughs) I love it.

11:53.208 --> 11:54.917
-MARTY: Captain Larry.
-Marty. How are you doing?

11:55.042 --> 11:56.875
-This is my buddy Matty Blake.
-Matty.

11:57.000 --> 11:58.000
-Nice to meet you. I'm Larry.
-Permission to come aboard?

11:58.167 --> 11:59.667
Absolutely.
Come on aboard, fellas.

11:59.750 --> 12:02.208
NARRATOR: Rounding out
the treasure-hunting team

12:02.333 --> 12:04.125
led by Bob Kreipke

12:04.208 --> 12:07.625
is magnetometer expert
and master diver Doug Gossage,

12:07.708 --> 12:11.833
underwater archaeologist
Rob Westrick

12:11.917 --> 12:13.958
and local expert diver
Luke Clyburn,

12:14.042 --> 12:16.500
who has more than six decades
of experience

12:16.625 --> 12:18.625
in the frigid waters
of Lake Michigan.

12:18.750 --> 12:20.208
Are we gonna find
something today, Bob?

12:20.375 --> 12:23.542
-Oh.
-NARRATOR: Piloting the team's
46-foot search vessel,

12:23.667 --> 12:27.167
the <i>Viking,</i>
is Captain Larry Barbeau.

12:27.292 --> 12:29.667
-MARTY: That's our crew,
then, right?
-MATTY: This is everybody.

12:29.792 --> 12:31.417
-How's the waters, Larry?
-LARRY: It shouldn't be
that bad today.

12:31.542 --> 12:33.167
It's supposed to be pretty calm.
Where we're gonna be at,

12:33.333 --> 12:34.583
we should be protected
by the island,

12:34.708 --> 12:35.833
-so we should be all right.
-MARTY: Okay.

12:35.958 --> 12:37.542
Isn't that what the guy
said that sunk out there?

12:37.667 --> 12:38.583
-(all laugh)
-That's the same thing he said,

12:38.708 --> 12:39.958
-so...
-MARTY: That's what I thought.

