and I are gonna be in the water.

23:22.875 --> 23:24.500
So, Marty's gonna be
on the surface comm.

23:24.667 --> 23:26.667
He'll be able to talk to us,

23:26.792 --> 23:28.500
-and we'll be able
to respond to him.
-Great.

23:28.667 --> 23:29.917
And then I'm gonna have

23:30.042 --> 23:32.750
a video camera,
and it's got an umbilical cord

23:32.875 --> 23:34.000
up to the boat.

23:34.125 --> 23:35.667
And Marty will be able to see...

23:35.792 --> 23:37.500
-MARTY: What you're seeing.
-...what I'm pointing at.

23:37.625 --> 23:39.000
-Oh, fantastic.
-Yeah.

23:39.125 --> 23:40.417
NARRATOR:
Diver Luke Clyburn

23:40.542 --> 23:42.000
will also be deploying

23:42.167 --> 23:46.292
the JW Fishers Pulse 8X
underwater metal detector,

23:46.375 --> 23:48.500
capable of scanning
for ferrous targets

23:48.583 --> 23:51.250
at depths of up to 200 feet.

23:51.375 --> 23:53.500
Luke will scan any debris

23:53.625 --> 23:56.333
to try to determine
whether it's a ship's part

23:56.417 --> 23:59.917
that could have belonged
to the <i>Captain Lawrence.</i>

24:00.042 --> 24:01.875
All right, we're here.
We're gonna throw the anchor in.

24:02.000 --> 24:03.583
We'll have Noel throw
the anchor in. Get us situated.

24:03.708 --> 24:05.500
And you guys can get in
the water and see what you find.

24:05.583 --> 24:07.167
All right, guys, suit up.
Let's go.

24:07.292 --> 24:08.458
-We're gonna try this.
-LUKE: Great.

24:08.542 --> 24:10.667
MATTY:
Once again,

24:10.792 --> 24:14.333
we have a dream team assembled
for a mystery like this

24:14.458 --> 24:15.875
and specifically this one.
I mean,

24:16.042 --> 24:18.792
Doug Gossage
is incredible at what he does,

24:18.875 --> 24:20.458
using that magnetometer
to get scans.

24:20.583 --> 24:23.208
Also has a wealth
of diving experience,

24:23.333 --> 24:25.000
so he's perfect for the job.

24:25.125 --> 24:26.708
And, uh, Luke Clyburn, who's got

24:26.875 --> 24:30.000
literally thousands of hours
with dives

24:30.083 --> 24:31.958
in Lake Michigan
and the Great Lakes.

24:32.083 --> 24:34.583
So, I couldn't be diving
with two better people.

24:34.708 --> 24:38.000
Okay, guys, everybody okay?
Okay? Okay? Okay?

24:38.125 --> 24:39.917
You got this, bud.

24:42.375 --> 24:44.042
We've done
all the equipment checks.

24:44.167 --> 24:45.417
We've gone over my gear.

24:45.542 --> 24:47.125
This is it. It's go time.

24:47.208 --> 24:48.500
In a sense,

24:48.583 --> 24:49.875
you're trying to find a needle
in a haystack,

24:50.042 --> 24:52.833
especially underwater,
so I'm excited

24:52.958 --> 24:54.375
-to see what we come up with.
-MARTY: Can you hear me,

24:54.542 --> 24:55.708
Matty?

24:58.250 --> 24:59.583
10-4.

25:10.958 --> 25:12.750
I feel, like, sort of
like a mother bear up here

25:12.875 --> 25:14.042
-or something, you know?
-(laughs)

25:14.167 --> 25:16.958
Some of my cubs
just went in the water.

25:28.792 --> 25:32.500
-BOB K.: Well, it looks pretty
flat here, doesn't it, Marty?
-MARTY: Yeah.

25:32.625 --> 25:34.708
This brings you back
to sobering reality, doesn't it?

25:34.875 --> 25:37.958
I mean this looks like stuff
that could cover up anything.

25:38.042 --> 25:39.833
-BOB K.: Yes. Yeah.
-MARTY: Yeah.

25:39.958 --> 25:41.750
Could be something
one inch below that.

25:41.875 --> 25:44.042
-Oh, absolutely. Yeah.
-And we're not seeing it.

25:45.250 --> 25:47.375
-BOB K.: Yeah.
-MARTY: Those guys
got their work

25:47.500 --> 25:49.625
-cut out for them down there.
-Yeah.

26:02.583 --> 26:04.542
Oh, yeah.

26:14.792 --> 26:17.750
Doug, do you think you're...
we're in the right spot?

26:21.042 --> 26:22.833
We think that's a good idea.
Heading out...

26:22.917 --> 26:25.958
out from the boat.
Head deeper. Over.

26:40.208 --> 26:43.833
We start making our way back
up that ledge from 50 feet up,

26:43.958 --> 26:45.833
and I see something,
and I point to it.

26:47.708 --> 26:49.333
What's that? What's that?

26:49.458 --> 26:51.708
Well, it's something,
it looks like.

26:54.667 --> 26:55.958
Here we go.

26:59.167 --> 27:00.917
It looks like a deadeye.

27:01.042 --> 27:03.917
They used deadeyes
on ships a lot,

27:04.042 --> 27:06.458
and they were
a round cylinder of wood

27:06.542 --> 27:10.583
with holes in them, which is
why they were called deadeyes.

27:10.708 --> 27:13.000
And you'd run the cabling
through those.

27:34.167 --> 27:36.875
NARRATOR: Just north of Poverty
Island in Lake Michigan...

27:39.667 --> 27:41.458
Does it have a name
carved in it?

27:41.542 --> 27:44.000
NARRATOR:
...Marty Lagina and Matty Blake

27:44.083 --> 27:46.417
are providing help
to a treasure-hunting team

27:46.542 --> 27:48.667
searching for a shipwreck.

27:48.792 --> 27:51.542
One that sank in 1933,

27:51.667 --> 27:55.125
reportedly
just after it salvaged millions

27:55.208 --> 27:56.583
in Civil War gold.

27:56.708 --> 27:58.458
Matty and the other divers

27:58.583 --> 28:01.000
have just discovered
man-made objects

28:01.083 --> 28:03.542
that they hope are part
of a debris field

28:03.708 --> 28:05.500
that will lead them
to the lost vessel

28:05.625 --> 28:08.000
and its treasure.

28:08.125 --> 28:11.583
They can't bring it up,
though, can they?

28:11.708 --> 28:13.583
BOB K.:
The state of Michigan

28:13.708 --> 28:17.167
happens to have
some very strict rules.

28:17.292 --> 28:20.625
You can document things
that you find on the bottom.

28:20.708 --> 28:24.500
You can come back
and make some claims to them.

28:24.625 --> 28:27.083
You can see what it is there,

28:27.208 --> 28:30.708
especially when you're
rubbing away zebra mussels,

28:30.875 --> 28:32.958
but the state of Michigan
does not want you

28:33.083 --> 28:34.500
to bring it to the surface,

28:34.625 --> 28:36.292
even to verify it.

28:43.750 --> 28:45.458
Roger.

28:46.667 --> 28:48.833
We want to keep expanding
the search,

28:48.917 --> 28:50.875
but if something goes wrong
on coming up,

28:51.042 --> 28:52.500
you have to have
a little extra air.

28:52.583 --> 28:55.125
Kind of like an airplane
landing with sufficient fuel,

28:55.208 --> 28:57.167
you know,
to be able to take off again.

28:57.333 --> 28:58.500
It's kind of like that.

28:58.625 --> 29:00.125
So, when it gets
to a certain pressure,

29:00.208 --> 29:02.875
the rules are the dive's over.
Divers are coming up.

29:03.000 --> 29:04.667
Yeah, you got something.

29:04.792 --> 29:06.333
(chuckles)

29:06.417 --> 29:08.833
-A piece of it.
-Definitely shipwreck, yeah.

29:08.917 --> 29:11.292
We started out
and kind of went a little, uh...

29:11.375 --> 29:12.667
right towards the shore

29:12.792 --> 29:14.083
and down there
in a little deeper water.

29:14.208 --> 29:16.625
I think it was maybe 50 feet.
And, uh,

29:16.708 --> 29:19.875
I think we all saw it
all at the same time,

29:20.000 --> 29:21.083
and everybody
just kind of converged on it.

29:21.208 --> 29:22.667
MARTY:
Yeah, we saw it, too,

29:22.792 --> 29:23.958
-but we couldn't tell
what it was.
-Yeah, no,

29:24.042 --> 29:25.792
-it's shipwreck material.
It's...
-Yes!

29:25.875 --> 29:27.167
DOUG G.:
Oh, yeah.

29:27.250 --> 29:29.167
It's...

29:29.250 --> 29:30.667
Yeah.

29:30.792 --> 29:32.208
I-It's like a round, um,

29:32.375 --> 29:35.167
-you know,
about telephone size, pole size.
-Yep.

29:35.292 --> 29:37.500
-And it was a corner post
of some sort.
-That big?

29:37.625 --> 29:41.375
-Oh, yeah, it was, uh,
it was this high off the bottom.
-Oh.

29:41.500 --> 29:44.667
And that metal rod
was probably all of two feet,

29:44.833 --> 29:45.875
-two and a half feet.
-MATTY: Yeah.

29:46.042 --> 29:47.292
And it was... it was definitely,

29:47.375 --> 29:49.125
you know,
the kind of rod that they used

29:49.208 --> 29:50.500
-in shipwrecks.
-MARTY: That's great.
-MATTY: Back then?

29:50.667 --> 29:52.167
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, I've seen it lots.

29:52.250 --> 29:55.875
This artifact is part
of a ship that broke off

29:56.000 --> 29:58.167
in a pretty disastrous method

29:58.292 --> 30:00.958
because it's not
a complete artifact.

30:01.083 --> 30:03.833
It's just a-a small piece of it.

30:03.958 --> 30:06.000
So, it's consistent
with what we're looking for.

30:06.125 --> 30:07.417
So, where do we go from here?

30:11.958 --> 30:13.875
Okay. Well, let's get you
new tanks. Let's go.

30:14.042 --> 30:15.792
-MATTY: Great.
-Let's get you back
in the water.

30:20.875 --> 30:22.667
All right, here we go.

30:22.750 --> 30:24.417
Here we go again.

30:24.542 --> 30:26.500
MARTY:
We got one thing found.

30:26.583 --> 30:29.083
Great.
We-We're not skunked. Yay!

30:29.208 --> 30:31.208
But we need to find
some more stuff.

30:31.333 --> 30:32.625
We need a pointer.

30:32.708 --> 30:34.667
You have to start finding
that debris trail.

30:34.792 --> 30:36.333
Divers down.

30:40.875 --> 30:43.208
What are you seeing, Doug?
Anything we need to know?

30:47.375 --> 30:50.250
-Yeah, the sediment looks...
It does.
-MARTY: It looks firm.

30:50.375 --> 30:51.708
Correct me if I'm wrong,
but that would indicate

30:51.875 --> 30:53.458
that stuff should be
on the surface.

30:53.542 --> 30:55.333
Stuff should be.
Yeah, absolutely.

31:10.833 --> 31:12.833
Tree branch.

31:17.208 --> 31:19.583
MARTY:
Topside to Doug for air check.

31:19.708 --> 31:21.250
How much you got?

31:23.542 --> 31:25.125
Roger that.

31:26.125 --> 31:27.542
They still got
a little bit of time.

31:27.667 --> 31:29.250
Might find something yet.

31:30.833 --> 31:32.750
What we know about that ship,

31:32.875 --> 31:34.292
there's got to be
stuff down there.

31:34.375 --> 31:37.417
We-we might just be
not quite in the right area.

31:37.542 --> 31:40.167
-And the thing is if you miss it
by just a little bit...
-Yeah.

31:40.250 --> 31:43.500
-You miss by an inch,
you miss by a mile.
-ROB W.: Exactly.

31:56.083 --> 31:58.292
(detector whines)

32:02.167 --> 32:04.000
Wow.

32:04.125 --> 32:06.500
Hey Doug,
can you, uh, look at the timber

32:06.625 --> 32:08.542
and give me the dimensions?

32:14.875 --> 32:16.542
Standing by.

32:22.250 --> 32:25.542
Okay. You don't use
two-inch-thick wood for much.

32:36.708 --> 32:38.583
Sound like a ship piece to you?

32:38.708 --> 32:40.500
It does. Timber that long,

32:40.583 --> 32:43.167
that's a... that's a piece
of hull structure.

32:43.292 --> 32:45.500
-Has to be, right?
-It has to be.
It can't be anything else.

32:45.625 --> 32:49.250
MATTY:
We are in an area
that was an area of interest.

32:49.375 --> 32:52.292
We are diving based on data.

32:52.417 --> 32:55.083
This could be something
from the <i>Captain Lawrence.</i>

32:55.208 --> 32:57.542
That ship might have been
right above the gold

32:57.708 --> 33:00.083
or had the gold on board.

33:00.208 --> 33:02.833
So we might be real close.

33:02.917 --> 33:04.333
This is good news.

33:11.875 --> 33:13.042
NARRATOR:
Off the coast of Poverty Island

33:13.208 --> 33:14.958
in Lake Michigan...

33:16.917 --> 33:18.750
MARTY:
That's fantastic.

33:18.875 --> 33:22.333
NARRATOR: ...Marty Lagina,
Matty Blake and their team

33:22.417 --> 33:24.667
have found evidence
of a possible shipwreck

33:24.792 --> 33:26.542
connected to a fortune

33:26.667 --> 33:28.500
in lost Civil War gold.

33:30.375 --> 33:33.167
Matty Blake
is part of the dive team

33:33.292 --> 33:36.833
that's investigating
the underwater finds.

33:36.958 --> 33:38.542
Probably is an outer frame,

33:38.708 --> 33:40.292
would've wrapped
around the ship.

33:40.417 --> 33:42.792
Then it'd be
about the right age, too, then,

33:42.875 --> 33:44.625
-wouldn't it?
-It would be.

33:44.708 --> 33:48.042
Has it got any sort
of fasteners or anything in it?

33:48.167 --> 33:51.292
Doug, any-any evidence
of fasteners of some type

33:51.375 --> 33:52.750
or holes?

33:58.417 --> 34:02.417
ROB W.:
If we were to figure how
far spaced are the fasteners,

34:02.542 --> 34:03.417
you know, based on that,

34:03.542 --> 34:05.458
you know how far away
those ribs were,

34:05.542 --> 34:06.708
and you can determine

34:06.833 --> 34:08.917
a rough guess to how long
the vessel would have been.

34:09.042 --> 34:11.292
And if it matches up
with the <i>Captain Lawrence,</i>

34:11.417 --> 34:13.542
it's another piece
of the puzzle.

34:29.667 --> 34:32.708
-They stirred up the bottom.
-They must be stirring up
the bottom, yeah.

34:53.375 --> 34:55.458
Okay. Surface as you need to.

35:02.542 --> 35:05.417
That's great, guys. Well done.

35:05.542 --> 35:07.833
I think it's
the <i>Captain Lawrence.</i> I'm gonna

35:07.958 --> 35:09.125
-choose to believe it.
-Yeah.

35:09.250 --> 35:11.292
So, where are the chests, Bob?

35:11.375 --> 35:15.208
If it drifted this way,
it's back there.

35:15.333 --> 35:18.333
You're finding a piece,
you got a starting point,

35:18.500 --> 35:20.458
-and from there...
-MARTY: Well,
we have two points now,

35:20.542 --> 35:22.500
so when we plot those
when we get up,

35:22.667 --> 35:24.708
that could be
really interesting.

35:24.833 --> 35:27.333
-BOB K.: Sure.
-MARTY: I don't know
of anybody underwater

35:27.458 --> 35:29.542
that ever sort of just went in

35:29.667 --> 35:32.708
and dove and found something,
like, you know, in five minutes.

35:32.875 --> 35:34.458
We'd have to hire
a team of divers

35:34.583 --> 35:36.375
and search
this whole bloody channel.

35:37.375 --> 35:39.167
BOB K.:
We had always speculated

35:39.292 --> 35:41.042
that we would not find

35:41.167 --> 35:44.250
a pristine, intact ship
on the bottom there.

35:44.375 --> 35:46.000
The Coast Guard reports

35:46.125 --> 35:48.917
say the ship
got smashed into pieces.

35:49.042 --> 35:51.042
So we were suspecting

35:51.167 --> 35:54.042
it would be a "debris field."

35:54.167 --> 35:58.875
And that debris field
could stretch a ways.

35:59.000 --> 36:00.167
I think that was
an excellent dive.

36:00.333 --> 36:01.792
MARTY:
We're running out of daylight.

36:01.875 --> 36:03.917
These guys are tired and
they're cold. We're calling it.

36:04.042 --> 36:05.792
But we moved the dial.
We're on the boat.

36:05.875 --> 36:07.250
We're happy. We're safe.

36:07.375 --> 36:09.333
If I had to ask you
for a percentage,

36:09.500 --> 36:11.000
was that a piece
of a wooden ship, what is it?

36:11.167 --> 36:13.208
100%! I like that number.

36:13.375 --> 36:14.750
That's a good number.

36:14.875 --> 36:16.333
Well, here's what occurs to me.

36:16.500 --> 36:17.958
We did a hell of a lot better
than last year.

36:18.042 --> 36:19.333
I mean, last year,
we were kind of

36:19.458 --> 36:20.417
find the needle in the haystack.

36:20.542 --> 36:22.167
Here, we brought
a lot more together.

36:22.250 --> 36:24.125
We had coordinates.
We had you guys.

36:24.208 --> 36:25.667
And we did a lot better.

36:25.792 --> 36:28.125
But, you know, the scary bit
is that this is like a...

36:28.208 --> 36:30.250
This is, like,
just keeps sucking you in.

36:30.375 --> 36:32.583
If you were on this quest alone,

36:32.708 --> 36:34.292
-let's say it was your deal...
-Yes.

36:34.375 --> 36:35.458
Would you keep coming back now?

36:35.542 --> 36:36.667
You seen enough
to have you come back?

36:36.792 --> 36:39.333
Yeah, I would.
It's intrigued me enough now,

36:39.458 --> 36:41.792
uh, I-I want to find this ship.

36:41.917 --> 36:43.333
MARTY:
That's great, guys.

36:43.417 --> 36:44.792
Well done. You're probably cold.

36:44.875 --> 36:46.667
-Freezing but exhilarated.
-MARTY: Yeah, let's...

36:46.792 --> 36:48.333
let's get this boat to shore
and see if we can get you

36:48.458 --> 36:50.667
-a cup of hot coffee.
-(laughs)

36:54.708 --> 36:56.417
DOUG G.:
I think <i>Captain Lawrence</i>

36:56.542 --> 36:59.542
warrants more investigation,
because we will find

36:59.708 --> 37:01.125
more debris.

37:01.250 --> 37:03.208
We will probably find
more planking.

37:03.333 --> 37:05.167
And hopefully,
we'll find something

37:05.292 --> 37:07.833
that would prove that it was
the <i>Captain Lawrence.</i>

37:09.125 --> 37:10.667
MARTY:
Here's the bald truth.

37:10.792 --> 37:12.833
I-I was pretty sure
we weren't gonna find chests

37:13.000 --> 37:16.083
strapped together with
.45 billion dollars in them.

37:16.208 --> 37:17.708
I didn't think
that was gonna happen

37:17.833 --> 37:19.250
on a couple-day dive.

37:19.375 --> 37:22.500
Uh, am I happy with the results,
though? Yes.

37:22.625 --> 37:24.875
Luke has seen intact wrecks,

37:25.000 --> 37:27.333
and yet he's still impressed
with what we found.

37:27.458 --> 37:30.583
And Doug has found
a lot of stuff down by Florida,

37:30.708 --> 37:32.000
and he's impressed
with what we found.

37:32.125 --> 37:33.833
So, that's infectious.
I'm happy.

37:34.000 --> 37:36.375
MATTY:
Well, there's a guy
that's gonna be very interested

37:36.500 --> 37:38.042
and missed what we did today,
and that's your brother, Rick.

37:38.208 --> 37:39.500
MARTY:
He will.

37:47.958 --> 37:50.708
MATTY: Well, I mean, just even
seeing Poverty Island, you know,

37:50.875 --> 37:52.625
coming up on it,
everything you said about it,

37:52.708 --> 37:55.667
I believed you intellectually,
but to see it,

37:55.750 --> 37:57.167
it-it almost
didn't do it justice,

37:57.292 --> 37:58.583
'cause I was like,
"Yes, now I get it."

37:58.708 --> 38:00.917
-The place is spooky.
-Yeah.

38:01.042 --> 38:02.667
What, to me, stood out, though,

38:02.833 --> 38:05.000
in terms
of what we were there to do

38:05.083 --> 38:06.375
was I found it,

38:06.500 --> 38:08.625
like,
a very mitigating circumstance

38:08.708 --> 38:11.500
that if I'm gonna make a run
for open water,

38:11.625 --> 38:13.042
be it through there
or through there,

38:13.208 --> 38:15.208
this is a great area
to dump my treasure

38:15.333 --> 38:16.750
before I make a break for it.

38:16.875 --> 38:18.375
And when you're kind of tucked
behind that island

38:18.500 --> 38:20.042
on the north side,

38:20.167 --> 38:22.583
it suddenly kind of made sense
to me as a good place to look.

38:22.708 --> 38:25.333
We did what divers could do,
but, you know,

38:25.458 --> 38:27.667
this looks little on this map,
but it's big.

38:27.792 --> 38:30.458
But anyway, I-I'm convinced
that this is worth another go.

38:30.542 --> 38:33.167
And in that... in that vein,

38:33.292 --> 38:35.583
uh, I actually got Bob
standing by,

38:35.708 --> 38:38.458
and he-he tells me
he's got some-some new data.

38:38.542 --> 38:39.708
So, I think we should
bring him up on the screen,

38:39.875 --> 38:41.375
-Matty, he's... It's all set.
-Yeah.

38:41.500 --> 38:42.833
It's all set up. And we'll...
Let's see what he says.

38:42.917 --> 38:44.500
-Yeah, absolutely. He's the guy.
-You know...

38:44.667 --> 38:46.792
-You know the passion he has.
-He's the guy.

38:46.917 --> 38:49.625
-MATTY: There he is.
-MARTY: Hello, Bob.
-RICK: Hi, Bob.

38:49.750 --> 38:51.917
<i>-How are you doing?</i>
-We're doing well.

38:52.042 --> 38:53.083
How are you?

38:53.208 --> 38:55.458
I'm doing well myself.

38:55.583 --> 38:57.917
Great. Well, I've got Matty here

38:58.042 --> 39:00.083
and, of course,
big brother Rick.

39:00.208 --> 39:01.917
And I know
you've been crunching through

39:02.042 --> 39:03.917
what we recovered
in the pictures,

39:04.042 --> 39:05.667
but you kind of mentioned

39:05.792 --> 39:08.208
that you've got some...
something new up your sleeve

39:08.333 --> 39:09.583
that might really help.

39:09.708 --> 39:10.875
Is that correct?

39:11.000 --> 39:13.500
Hey, listen, we're working
on something right now

39:13.583 --> 39:16.583
which I think will be
a major breakthrough.

39:19.458 --> 39:21.833
MARTY:
Well, I'm wanting
to hear about that.

39:25.708 --> 39:28.708
-MARTY: What've you got?
-Well, based on our dives

39:28.875 --> 39:31.375
<i>that we took last time, we tok
some of that information,</i>

39:31.500 --> 39:33.333
and we crunched it down,

39:33.458 --> 39:35.458
and I looked
at some of the old records

39:35.542 --> 39:37.167
about the wind conditions
and that,

39:37.292 --> 39:39.417
and hey, I'm ready to go again.

39:39.542 --> 39:43.833
<i>And we've got a new piece
of equipment at our access.</i>

39:44.000 --> 39:47.000
It's an R.O.V. We've got
complete control over it,

39:47.125 --> 39:49.875
<i>and it does have one cord</i>

39:50.000 --> 39:52.333
that brings up the video
and th-- and the controls.

39:52.458 --> 39:54.292
Can we cover more ground, Bob?

39:54.417 --> 39:55.500
Because that's what
I'm convinced,

39:55.625 --> 39:56.875
in our first two attempts,

39:57.000 --> 39:58.208
we just couldn't
cover enough ground.

39:58.375 --> 40:00.458
<i>Yes, this device can cover,</i>

40:00.542 --> 40:03.833
you know, at one crack,
600 feet.

40:04.000 --> 40:06.375
That sounds great.
Diving on an actual picture.

40:06.500 --> 40:08.042
<i>-Yes.</i>
-All right.
Eyes and fins, right?

40:08.208 --> 40:09.250
Eyes and fins.

40:09.375 --> 40:11.417
I'd be so much more
comfortable, too,

40:11.542 --> 40:13.333
now doing it again
and having an image

40:13.500 --> 40:15.000
to dive on as opposed to a hit.

40:15.125 --> 40:17.667
I mean, Bob, we might have
been close last time,

40:17.750 --> 40:20.583
because the divers
showed us pictures...

40:20.708 --> 40:23.833
<i>-Yes.</i>
-...of what you-you felt
might be the rib of a schooner.

40:24.000 --> 40:25.667
-Which would fit.
-Yes.

40:25.792 --> 40:27.667
I've become convinced that this

40:27.833 --> 40:30.333
is well worth pursuing still,

40:30.500 --> 40:32.417
but the next time,
we got to throw more at it.

40:32.542 --> 40:34.458
We got to cover more ground,

40:34.583 --> 40:35.917
we got to, we got to get
a little more rigorous

40:36.042 --> 40:37.333
about how we do this.

40:37.458 --> 40:38.917
But sounds like
you're prepared to do that.

40:39.042 --> 40:40.917
Oh, yes. I agree.

40:41.042 --> 40:42.958
I'm all in.
I want another crack at it.

40:43.042 --> 40:45.333
Yeah, I-I do, too.
I-I just like this one.

40:45.500 --> 40:47.250
I like it for all kinds
of different reasons.

40:47.375 --> 40:48.833
I agree, uh, this is
well worth pursuing.

40:49.000 --> 40:51.250
I mean,
it's-it's in your backyard.

40:51.375 --> 40:52.708
Wha-- Who's gonna
walk away from that?

40:52.833 --> 40:55.083
MARTY:
Bob, I thank you, as always.

40:55.208 --> 40:57.625
You know, you always get us
re-excited about the venture.

40:57.708 --> 41:00.167
So, we will proceed,
and I'll be glad to meet you

41:00.292 --> 41:02.583
out there in the open waters
of Lake Michigan, okay?

41:02.708 --> 41:04.917
-You take care.
-RICK: Take care, Bob.
Good luck.

41:05.042 --> 41:08.417
<i>-Sounds good. Thanks.</i>
-MATTY: Thanks, Bob.
Until the next time.

41:08.542 --> 41:11.500
Ugh, that was incredible.

41:11.583 --> 41:13.417
You know, guys like that,
it's funny.

41:13.542 --> 41:16.000
We keep running
into characters like this

41:16.083 --> 41:17.958
who are doggedly determined.

41:18.083 --> 41:20.833
They're turned on by a story,
and then they just won't quit.

41:20.917 --> 41:23.042
Is it something about
the word "treasure,"

41:23.167 --> 41:24.917
or is it something about

41:25.042 --> 41:27.667
-the ability of human beings...
-Now you know what
the word is, Rick?

41:27.792 --> 41:30.292
...to commit to endeavors
that nothing

41:30.375 --> 41:32.500
can dissuade them
from pursuing it?

41:32.625 --> 41:35.000
The word is "quest."
It's a quest.

41:35.083 --> 41:37.167
MATTY:
There's kind of like
a list of ingredients

41:37.292 --> 41:38.542
-that make these things special.
-Yes.

41:38.708 --> 41:39.583
I don't think there's
one example where it's like:

41:39.708 --> 41:41.667
"Well, a guy buried some gold,

41:41.833 --> 41:43.708
I want that gold," it's always,
"There was espionage,"

41:43.875 --> 41:45.333
-or "There was
a dumping of treasure."
-There's a story.

41:45.458 --> 41:46.750
"There's a story
of a young kid seeing..."

41:46.875 --> 41:48.250
MARTY: And usually,
history's intertwined.

41:48.375 --> 41:49.750
-History's intertwined. Yes.
-Upheavals.

41:49.875 --> 41:51.292
You know,
there's a lot of common threads

41:51.417 --> 41:53.792
that run through
all of these quests.

41:53.875 --> 41:55.750
Yeah, agreed.

41:55.875 --> 41:57.750
But we got a great big one
to attend to right here.

41:57.875 --> 42:00.167
-So, let's-let's get back at it.
Got a lot of work.
-Sure do.

42:00.292 --> 42:02.000
MATTY:
Good job, fellas. That was fun.

42:02.083 --> 42:03.500
MARTY:
Yeah.

